**What it does now:**
- Tracks every file the loader touches in a `Map<file, {loaded, total}>`.
- Aggregate % = `sum(loaded) / max(sum(total), 3.1 GB known total)`.
- Monotonic clamp — if the underlying ratio dips (e.g. a new 1.5 GB file
  appears and inflates the denominator), the displayed % stays at its
  previous max instead of jumping back.

So the bar should now climb from 0% → 100% steadily, with occasional brief
  pauses (when a new big file's bytes haven't started arriving yet) but
  never going backwards.

If you've already partially loaded the model in this browser session,
  IndexedDB-cached files will report `done` immediately, which the new code
  handles by clamping each cached file to its full size — so the bar should
  jump quickly through cached portions and then climb steadily through the
  rest.

❯ After I download the model, I can ask the chat, then I got this error
  Generation failed: Unknown ArrayValue filter: trim

● That error is from `@huggingface/jinja` — the chat-template engine doesn't
  define a `trim` filter for arrays, but the Gemma 4 template applies `|
  trim` to `message['content']`. We're forcing every message's content to be
  an array (`[{ type: "text", text: ... }]`), so `| trim` fails on the
  system message.

The fix: send text-only content as **plain strings**, not as multimodal
  content arrays. The Gemma 4 template handles both forms; arrays are only
  required when you actually have an image or audio.

